<subSubSection id="6A886DFF7BA64CA15C73EF7CDF77F073" pageId="15" pageNumber="100" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="16B526FDB35EFED92C3A240204CD52F6" pageId="15" pageNumber="100">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B9B18916F82DAA379F1EE72A09228AA0" pageId="15" pageNumber="100">
This species-group name is based on the Greek adjective 
<normalizedToken id="B359A9C0253618A1F93C533FE3C05CFE" originalValue="“adelos”">&quot;adelos&quot;</normalizedToken>
, meaning 
<normalizedToken id="1ABC0A08A75F8C072E771FF7FAAF15B0" originalValue="“indistinct”">&quot;indistinct&quot;</normalizedToken>
or 
<normalizedToken id="C3883E9E1C1E8361F472F0E82A40D229" originalValue="“inconspicuous”">&quot;inconspicuous&quot;</normalizedToken>
, in reference to its lack of bluish reflection on the ventral forewing. This species-group name is treated as a Latinized feminine adjective in accordance with the feminine generic name.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B28627650C84A20949B9F988E8AE9BE6" pageId="15" pageNumber="100" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="708D2645241EA8ABC0067620BD819703" pageId="15" pageNumber="100">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph id="124396B03BA06C433E31095C86CBDEE9" pageId="15" pageNumber="100">(Fig. 6). This subspecies occurs from Nicaragua to western Ecuador.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
